<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910710-0025</DOCNO><DOCID>910710-0025.</DOCID><HL>   South Africa Is Reinstated   By the Olympic Committee</HL><DATE>07/10/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><RE>AFRICA (AF)EUROPE (EU)SOUTH AFRICA (SF)SWITZERLAND (SZ)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- South Africa was readmittedto the Olympic movement after a 21-year suspension, clearingthe way for South African athletes to compete in the 1992games.   The last time South Africa competed in the Olympics was in1960 in Rome. The country was expelled from the InternationalOlympic Committee in 1970 because of its policy of apartheid,or racial segregation.</LP><TEXT>   South Africa fulfilled the IOC's main condition forreinstatement in June, when parliament repealed the lastlegal pillars of apartheid. The South Africans also havelargely complied with the IOC's demand to unite the country'sracially separate sports federations into single nonracialentities.   The announcement was made by IOC President Juan AntonioSamaranch after talks with a South African sports delegation.&quot;It is really an important day not only for the Olympicmovement but for all sports around the world,&quot; Mr. Samaranchsaid. &quot;I would like to see very soon athletes and playersfrom South Africa taking part in major sports competitionsaround the world.&quot;   Mr. Samaranch and the IOC's executive board approved SouthAfrica's readmission after it was recommended by the IOC'scommission on apartheid.</TEXT></DOC>